@NODE "Install" "Installation"
@TOC "MAIN"

          Installation and use

          For installation, see file PMP-Readme in the PMP directory.

          Once  installed,  ensure  that the current directory is PMP, and
          type  PMP  to  run the program.  You should shortly be presented
          with the @{"Configuration Screen" LINK "Config"}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Config" "Configuration Screen"
@TOC "MAIN"

          Configuration Screen.

          This is the first screen you see after loading the program.
          The following gadgets are available here:

          - Display        PAL  or  NTSC.   Depending on the country you
                           live  in,  your  TV  or  Monitor  will be PAL
                           or NTSC.  Use this option  to  select the one
                           you require.

          - Star Data      Yes  or  No.   If "Yes" is selected, then the
                           program  will load and use the star database.
                           You can select "No" if you aren't  interested
                           in the  stars,  or if you don't have 1 meg of
                           free memory. If  the  star  database  is  not
                           loaded,  the  program also runs a bit faster.
                           This  is   ideal  for   use  in  eclipse   or
                           Sun/Moon/Planetary work.

          - Text Font      Custom or Default.  The program contains it's
                           own  custom  font.  This will be  used if the
                           Custom option is selected.  If  the "Default"
                           option is selected, then the program will use
                           whatever font your system is currently using.

          - Save           Click   this   to   make  your  configuration
                           permanent.   It  is  saved  in  a file called
                           S:PMP-Config

          - Cancel         Click  this  to quit if you decide not to use
                           the planetarium after all.                    

          - Ok             Click  this  to  enter  the  main planetarium
                           program. After several seconds (calculating!)
                           the @{"Main Screen" LINK "MainScr"} should appear.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "MainScr" "Main Screen"
@TOC "MAIN"

          Main Screen.

          The  Main  Screen  is  the main planetarium display.
          It operates in one of two modes:  @{"Sky Mode" LINK "SkyMode"} and @{"Orbit Mode" LINK "OrbitMode"}.  When
          the  program  loads  it  is in Sky Mode.  Orbit Mode is selected
          from the @{"View Menu" LINK "ViewMenu"} or by pressing [\] (Slash).

          Main Screen functions:

            @{"Object Information" LINK "ClickInfo"}
            @{"About Requester" LINK "About"}
            @{"Calendar Requester" LINK "Calendar"}
            @{"World Map Requester" LINK "WorldMap"}
            @{"Auto Clock Requester" LINK "AutoClock"}
            @{"Preferences Requester" LINK "Prefs"}
            @{"File Requester" LINK "FileReq"}
            @{"Error Display" LINK "ErrorDisp"}
            @{"Animation System" LINK "Anim"}

          Main Screen menus

           In  the  description of each menu, the letter or word in square
           brackets  indicates  a  keyboard shortcut for a menu item.  The
           case  is  important here.  For example, to Quit, you must press
           Shift/Q to get a capital Q.

           @{"PROJECT MENU" LINK "ProjectMenu"}
           @{"FIND MENU" LINK "FindMenu"}
           @{"ANIM MENU" LINK "AnimMenu"}
           @{"VIEW MENU" LINK "ViewMenu"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "SkyMode" "Sky Mode"
@TOC "MAIN"

          Sky Mode.

          Sky Mode gives a view of the sky as seen by an observer standing
          on  the  Earth's  surface  at a particular place and time.  This
          display  attempts  to  depict the sky in the most attractive and
          realistic  way possible.  For best effect it is recommended that
          the  program  is  used  in  a darkened room.  To set the monitor
          brightness and contrast correctly, proceed as follows:  Refer to
          the  description  of  "@{"Calendar" LINK "Calendar"}" to set the time to midnight, so
          that  you  get  a  display  of  stars.   Now  adjust the monitor
          brightness  so  that  the  black  parts  of the picture are just
          visible  as  grey.  Then turn it down a fraction.  Next, set the
          contrast  so  that  the  brightest  stars appear bright, but not
          blurred,  and  so  that  the dark blue sky is just visible.  You
          should  get  quite  a  realistic looking picture.  The stars are
          generally  blueish  rather  than  white as I think it looks more
          like the (my?) naked eye sees them.

          The Sky Mode display contains an optional Status Line, which
          gives the following information:

           a) Time and Date of the current view.

           b) Latitude and Longitude of the current view.

           c) Azimuth and Altitude  of the observer (ie: Which way you are
              looking, or your bearings).

           d) View angle,  ie: The number of degrees of sky represented by
              the screen width.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "OrbitMode" "Orbit Mode"
@TOC "MAIN"

          Orbit Mode.

          Orbit Mode gives a view of the solar system as seen from a great
          distance.   It  can be used to follow the motions of the planets
          in their orbits.

          The Orbit Mode display contains an optional Status Line, which
          gives the following information:

           a) Time and Date of the current view.

           b) View range, ie: The number of Astronomical Units (AU)
              represented by the screen width.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "ClickInfo" "Object Information"
@TOC "MainScr"

          Object Information.

          To  get  information  on an object, position the pointer near it
          and  click  the  left mouse button.  There is no need to hit the
          exact  point  where  the  object is as the program looks for the
          nearest  object  within  a small radius.  This should bring up a
          small  display  at the bottom of the @{"Main Screen" LINK "MainScr"} which is called
          the @{"Object Ident Display" LINK "ObjIdent"}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "ObjIdent" "Object Ident Display"
@TOC "MainScr"

          Object Ident Display.

          This  display  contains information  and  gadgets.  From left to
          right, these are as follows:

          - Close Gadget   Makes the Ident Display go away.
          - Information    Gives the name of the object.
          - Info Gadget    Opens a large "@{"Info Display" LINK "ObjInfo"}" with more details.
          - Track Gadget   Tracks the object and closes the Ident Display.
          - Find Gadget    Looks towards object and closes Ident display.
          - Cols Gadget    Cycles through four colour schemes.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "ObjInfo" "Object Info Display"
@TOC "MainScr"

          Object Info Display.

          This  display  contains  detailed  information,  a  picture, and
          gadgets.   It is brought up by clicking the "Info" gadget in the
          Ident  Display.   The  top part of the display is similar to the
          Ident Display.  From left to right it is as follows:

          - Close Gadget  Makes all information displays go away.
          - Text          Gives the name of the object.
          - Exit Gadget   Closes the info display.
          - Track Gadget  Tracks the object, and exits the Info Display.
          - Find Gadget   Looks towards object and exits Info Display.
          - Cols Gadget   Cycles through four colour schemes.

          The  left  part  of  the  display gives astronomical information
          about  the  object,  such as it's position, brightness, distance
          from   Earth,   etc.   This  information  should  be  useful  to
          astronomers  but  may  not  mean much to the beginner.  For more
          information you should refer to a good astronomy book.

          The  right  part of the display is an illustration.  In the case
          of Planets, Sun and Moon it gives a small picture of the object.
          If you click on this picture, a full screen picture will appear.
          This can be removed by clicking on it.

          In  the  case  of stars, it gives a diagram of the constellation
          which  contains  that star.  The relevant star is indicated by a
          small  arrow.  If the "Greek Letters" option is switched on
          (See  @{"Preferences" LINK "Prefs"}),  then  the main stars in the diagram will be
          identified  by  greek  letters.  Again, see any decent astronomy
          book  for  an  explanation  of this.  If you click on one of the
          stars,  the  info  display closes and re-opens with that star as
          the subject.

          Finally,  most  objects  will  have  some descriptive text about
          them.  It is here that you will find information about the Solar
          System,  or learn the Mythology of the constellations.  If there
          is  more  than  one  page  of text, the next page can be seen by
          clicking the "More" gadget.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "About" "The About Requester"
@TOC "MainScr"

          The About Requester.

          This  gives  information  about the version of the program, date
           written,  and available memory.   To exit from it,  click on the
          "Ok" gadget.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Calendar" "The Calendar Requester"
@TOC "MainScr"

          The Calendar Requester.

          This  is  the  most  complex  requester  in  the program.  It is
          effectively the control panel of your own personal Time Machine.
          You  use  the  gadgets  to change the time of your observations.
          Despite  it's  complexity, it is very easy to use.  To change an
          item,  simply  click on the associated Up Arrow to increase it's
          value, and the Down Arrow to decrease it's value.

          Each item on the requester will now be described:

          - LCT   HH:MM:SS WWW DD MMM YYYY YY

          This  is  the current setting of "Local Civil Time" (LCT).  This
          is  the  time we use in everyday life.  When we say "It's twenty
          past one" we are referring to time as measured by LCT.

          - LST   HH:MM:SS

          This  is  the  current  setting  of "Local Sidereal Time" (LST).
          This  is  the  local  time  as  measured  by  the  stars.  It is
          different  to LCT because as the Earth moves around the Sun, the
          star  positions  appear  to change and the stars rise about four
          minutes  earlier  every  night.   If  we  know  the  LST and the
          coordinates  of a star, we can calculate where it will be in the
          sky.   Refer  to  any  good book on astronomy for details on how
          this works.

          - JD NNNNNNN.NNNN

          This  shows  the  Julian  Day  number  which is expressed as the
          number  of  days since 1st January 4713 BC.  It is computed from
          the  date and time that you set, and is used in the astronomical
          calculations.

          - Zone  NN

          This  shows  your  time  zone  as  a number of hours East of the
          Greenwich  Meridian.   Negative  values  indicate  the number of
          hours  West  of  Greenwich.   It  works  in conjunction with the
          longitude  you  set  in  the World Map Requester.  If you change
          this value, your longitude will change to keep it consistent.

          - DS    NN

          This  allows  you  to compensate for "Daylight Saving" time.  In
          Britain this is called British Summer Time.  When the clocks are
          an  hour ahead of Greenwich Mean Time, you should set this value
          to 1.

          - LOCAL NOON

          Click on this to set the LCT to 12:00:00 on the current date.

          - LOCAL MIDNIGHT

          Click on this to set the LCT to 00:00:00 on the current date.

          - LOCAL TIME NOW

          Click on this to set the LCT  (and date)  to that of the Amiga's
          internal clock.

          - UT    HH:MM:SS WWW DD MMM YYYY YY

          This  is  the current setting of "Universal Time" (UT).  This is
          the  time as used by astronomers.  It is practically the same as
          Greenwich  Mean  Time  (GMT)  which  is  used  to broadcast time
          signals  around the world on the radio.  In Britain, when Summer
          Time  is  not  in  force, UT, GMT and LCT are basically the same
          thing   (although   technically   I   believe  there  are  small
          differences).

          - GST   HH:MM:SS

          This  is the current setting of "Greenwich Sidereal Time" (GST).
          This is the same as LST but as measured at Greenwich rather than
          at the observer's local position.

          Key:    HH      - Hour     eg: 12
                  MM      - Minute   eg: 09
                  SS      - Second   eg: 50
                  WWW     - Weekday  eg: Wed
                  DD      - Day      eg: 11
                  MMMM    - Month    eg: Aug
                  YYYY YY - Year     eg: 1999 AD

                  N indicates a digit.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "WorldMap" "The World Map Requester"
@TOC "MainScr"

          The World Map Requester.

          This  consists  of  a simple map of the world, and some gadgets.
          It is used to choose the position you wish to observe from.  You
          can do this quickly by simply clicking on the map.  You will see
          a white cross marking your location.  The latitude and longitude
          displays  underneath  the  picture  will update to show your new
          coordinates.    Alternatively,   you  can  directly  enter  your
          latitude  and longitude by clicking on the up/down arrows around
          the relevant displays.  The white cross will update to show your
          new  position  on  the  map.   Note  that  if  you  change  your
          longitude,  your  Time Zone value will also change (See @{"Calendar" LINK "Calendar"}
          section).  Generally, you will probably find it easiest to click
          on  the  map  about  where  you want to be, and then "fine-tune"
          using the arrow gadgets.

          The following gadgets are also available:

          - Save           Allows  you  to  save  the  location you have
                           chosen.  This means you can have files called
                           perhaps  "London.LOC",  or  "Paris.LOC" which
                           you  can then load quickly.  This way you can
                           keep  your  favourite  locations  on disk for
                           quick  access.   The  file  S:PMP-Location is
                           used to hold the initial startup location for
                           the program.  You can alter this if you wish.

          - Load           Allows you  to load  a  location  from  disk.

          - Ok             Click  here  to  view  the  sky  from the new
                           position.

          - Cancel         Click here  to forget your  changes and exit.

          NTSC users please note:  There is not enough room on your screen
          for  the  whole  map and the control panel, so you have an extra
          gadget  called  "Up/Down".   If you click this once, the control
          panel will move down to reveal the bottom part of the map.  Only
          the  top line of the gadget will be visible, right at the bottom
          left  of  the  display.   You  have to click it again to get the
          control panel back!

@ENDNODE

@NODE "AutoClock" "The Auto Clock Requester"
@TOC "MainScr"

          The Auto Clock Requester.

          This allows you to set the time increment for auto-update of the
          observer's  time.   You simply click on the arrow gadgets to set
          the (positive or negative) time interval in Years, Months, Days,
          Hours, Minutes and Seconds.

          The following gadgets are also available:

          - Ok             Click here  to exit  the requester  and start
                           the auto-clock running.

          - Clear          Click here  to clear  the display  to zeroes.
                           This also stops the auto-clock.

          - Cancel         Click here to forget your changes.

          Note:            The  key  Shift/A  can  be used to toggle the
                           auto-clock  on  and off while the @{"Main Screen" LINK "MainScr"}
                           is  visible.   Also,  when  the auto-clock is
                           running,  the program will be very busy doing
                           calculations  for 99% of the time, so any key
                           presses  or  menu selections may take a while
                           to  be  noticed.   If  in  doubt,  switch the
                           auto-clock  off  using  either  Shift/A or by
                           using the "Clear" gadget in the requester.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Prefs" "The Preferences Requester"
@TOC "MainScr"

          The Preferences Requester.

          This  allows  you  to switch various options on and off, and set
          other parameters which affect the way the program works.
          Some  of these options are only meaningful in @{"Sky Mode" LINK "SkyMode"}, and some
          have  a different effect depending on which mode the @{"Main Screen" LINK "MainScr"}
          is in.

          The following options are available:

          Option             Meaning if switched on
          ------             ----------------------

          - Horizon          Displays ground as a horizon-line.
                             (Sky Mode only).

          - Ground           Displays solid ground (Sky Mode only).

          - Atmosphere       Displays  sky in a shade of blue, and blots
                             out  stars  depending  on brightness.  Also
                             does  extra  calculations  for  atmospheric
                             refraction (Sky Mode only).

          - Status Line      Displays the status line.

          - Equator          Draws  a  dotted  line  on  the Main Screen
                             which   represents  the  celestial  equator
                             marked  out in one-hour divisions.  See any
                             good  astronomy  book for an explanation of
                             the celestial equator (Sky Mode only).

          - Ecliptic         Draws  a  dotted  line  on  the Main Screen
                             which  represents  the ecliptic, marked out
                             in  ten-degree  divisions.   See  any  good
                             astronomy  book  for  an explanation of the
                             ecliptic (Sky Mode only).

          - Greek Letters    Greek letters will appear on the diagram of
                             a constellation in the @{"Info Display" LINK "ObjInfo"}.

          - More Precise     Program  will  calculate  Sines and Cosines
                             instead of looking them up in a table.

          - Exaggerate       In  Sky  Mode, the Sun and Moon will not be
                             drawn  any  smaller  than  about  16 pixels
                             wide,  no matter how far you zoom out.  NB:
                             This    can    cause   spurious   incorrect
                             "eclipses"  to  occur  because the sizes of
                             the  Sun  and Moon are no longer "correct".
                             In  @{"Orbit Mode" LINK "OrbitMode"}, the Moon will be plotted at
                             an exaggerated distance from the Earth.

          - Back to Front    The  Main Screen  will  be  drawn  reversed
                             right to left (Sky Mode only).

          - Upside Down      The  Main Screen will be drawn reversed top
                             to bottom (Sky Mode only).

                             NB:   To  get the effect of looking through
                             an  astronomical telescope you will need to
                             select BOTH Back to Front AND Upside Down.

          - Sun              The Sun will be computed and displayed.  If
                             this  is  switched off, the program behaves
                             as  if  the  Sun  is  not shining, with the
                             exception  that  the  Moon and Planets will
                             still be visible.

          - Moon             The Moon will be computed and displayed.

          - Moon Detail      The Moon will have craters drawn on it.
                             (Sky Mode only).

          - Stars            The stars will be computed and displayed.
                             (Sky Mode only).

          - Colour           The stars and planets will show colours.

          - Trail            Each screen display  will be  drawn without
                             erasing  the  previous one.  This gives the
                             effect  of  "trails"  which  can be seen on
                             long  exposure photographs.  If the display
                             becomes  full  of  garbage  you can use the
                             "Refresh" menu item under the  "View" menu,
                             or press the "HELP" key.

          - Lines            Constellation  lines  will  be drawn on the
                             Main Screen.

          - Names            Constellation  names  will  be drawn on the
                             Main Screen.
 
          - Real Time        The  clock/calendar  will  be  set from the
                             system clock approximately every 10 seconds
                             and the display will be recalculated.

          - Mercury, Venus,  The  selected  planet  will be computed and
            Earth,Mars,      displayed.  The Earth  option only  affects
            Jupiter, Saturn, Orbit Mode.
            Uranus, Neptune,
            Pluto

          - Inverse          The Main Screen and constellations drawn on
                             the  Info  Display  are  drawn  in  inverse
                             colours.  This may be useful when using the
                             program  in  conjunction  with photographic
                             negatives.

          The following proportional gadgets are also available:

          - Gain Control

          This  is  a control which works a bit like the Gain Control on a
          video  camera.   It is usually set to zero, and can be turned up
          or  down  as required.  It effectively changes the brightness of
          the  stars and planets, so you can force them to shine through a
          full  daylight sky, or turn up the brightness a bit when you are
          using the program in a brightly lit room. This only works in Sky
          Mode.

          Gain Control keyboard shortcuts from Main Screen:

          [8]              Increases the gain value by 1.
          [KEYPAD /]       Increases the gain value by 1.
          [9]              Reduces   the gain value by 1.
          [KEYPAD *]       Reduces   the gain value by 1.

          - Max Magnitude

          This  adjusts  the  maximum  magnitude  of  stars  which will be
          computed  and  displayed.   For  instance, if you set it to +2.0
          then  no  stars  dimmer  than magnitude 2 will be considered for
          display.   So  if you are only interested in the brighter stars,
          you can speed up calculations by suppressing the fainter stars.

          Max Magnitude keyboard shortcuts from Main Screen:

          [0]              Sets max magnitude to 0.
          [1]              Sets max magnitude to 1.
          [2]              Sets max magnitude to 2.
          [3]              Sets max magnitude to 3.
          [4]              Sets max magnitude to 4.
          [5]              Sets max magnitude to 5.
          [6]              Sets max magnitude to 6.

          Other gadgets:

          - Ok               Click here  to  use  the  current settings,
                             and exit.

          - Save             Saves the  preferences to  file S:PMP-Prefs
                             These settings will then be  used next time
                             you run the program, or click on "Default".

          - Default          Resets the preferences  to  the last  saved
                             values.

          - Cancel           Click here to cancel any changes, and exit.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "FileReq" "The File Requester"
@TOC "MainScr"

          The File Requester.

          Whenever  the program needs you to specify a filename, it brings
          up  a  standard  file  requester.   This  contains  a  number of
          gadgets, as follows:

          - Names
          Up  to 12 file or disk names appear in the Name Box which is the
          large  area  nearest  to the top left of the requester.  You can
          click  on  one of them, and the effect it has will depend on the
          type of entry:

           If it  is a disk or assign name, then it will be entered in the
           Path String, and the contents of the new path will be displayed
           in the Name Box.

           If it  is  a  directory,  then  it will be appended to the Path
           String, and  the  contents of the new path will be displayed in
           the Name Box.

           If it is a file name, it will be highlighted and entered in the
           File String.

          - Scroll Bar
          To  the  right  of  the  names is a scroll bar.  You use this to
          scroll  through  the  list  of names.  When you click on it, the
          name  list  will  be  sorted into alphabetical order.  Above and
          below  the  scroll  bar  are  some  arrows.  They can be used to
          scroll through the names one entry at a time.

          - Path String
          This  shows the path name you have specified.  It can be changed
          by  either clicking in it and editing the string, by clicking
          on a directory name in the Name Box, or by clicking on "Parent".

          - File String
          This  shows the file name you have specified.  It can be changed
          by  either  clicking  in  it  and  editing  the  filename, or by
          clicking on one of the filenames in the Name Box.

          - Disks
          Click  here  to get a list of disk names in the Name Box.  These
          names are device names (eg: DH1:) or volume names.

          - Assigns
          Click  here to get a list of assigns in the Name Box.  These are
          names such as FONTS: or DEVS:

          - Parent
          Click here to go back a level in the path name.  For example, if
          the Path String is "DH1:PMP/PIC", then clicking on "Parent" will
          go back to "DH1:PMP", and then to "DH1:".

          Once  the  Path and File Strings contain the required file spec,
          click  on "Ok" to exit and start the disk operation, or "Cancel"
          to abort the operation and undo any changes you have made to the
          file requester.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "ErrorDisp" "The Error Display"
@TOC "MainScr"

          The Error Display.

          If  there is a disk error, then a red display will appear at the
          bottom of the screen giving an error message.  It can be removed
          by  clicking the close gadget on the far left.  The program will
          attempt  to  continue  the  best it can under the circumstances.
          For instance, if the file Moon.PIC was to be accidently deleted,
          the program would still work except it would not be able to draw
          the Moon picture anymore, and an error display would appear when
          it attempted to do so.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Anim" "The Animation System"
@TOC "MainScr"

          The Animation System.

          The  program  can record a sequence of @{"Main Screen" LINK "MainScr"} pictures, and
          replay them later.  The sequences can also be saved and reloaded
          for  later  use.   To  use this feature, you need the @{"Anim Menu" LINK "AnimMenu"}.
          The use of the options under this menu will now be described.

          If  you  select the "Record" option, the mouse pointer will have
          the word "REC" below it.  Every time the Main Screen is updated,
          it will be recorded in a list of animation frames in memory.

          To stop recording, select the "Stop" option.

          To record a single picture on it's own, select the "Record Once"
          option.

          The  newly recorded frames are always appended at the end of the
          list.

          To  play the sequence back, select the "Play" option.  The mouse
          pointer  will  have  the  word "PLAY" under it, and the sequence
          will be replayed.  You can make the sequence repeat indefinately
          by  pressing  the  "l"  key.   This  key  toggles  the "looping"
          function on and off.

          To stop playback, select the "Stop" option.

          You  can  also  play the sequence backwards ("Reverse Play"), or
          single  step  backwards  and forwards through the frames ("Frame
          Advance, Frame Back").

          You  can delete the frame you are currently viewing by selecting
          the "Delete Current" option.

          You  can  delete  all  the  frames by selecting the "Delete All"
          option.

          To save the currently stored sequence, select the "Save" option.
          Depending on how many frames you have recorded, this may take up
          quite a lot of disk space.  The frames are run-length encoded to
          save  some  space.   I find that an archiver like LhA can really
          squash  them  down  in  size.  This may be useful if you want to
          keep lots of animation files.

          To  load  a  previously  saved animation sequence (or one of the
          examples),  select the "Load" option.  You will normally need to
          first delete any current frames using the "Delete All" function,
          otherwise the newly loaded ones will be appended.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "ProjectMenu" "PROJECT MENU"
@TOC "MainScr"

          PROJECT MENU

          - About...
          Brings up the @{"About Requester" LINK "About"}.

          - Calendar...    [c]
          Brings up the @{"Calendar Requester" LINK "Calendar"}.

          - World Map...   [w]
          Brings up the @{"World Map requester" LINK "WorldMap"} (@{"Sky Mode" LINK "SkyMode"} only).

          - Auto Clock...  [a]
          Brings up the @{"Auto Clock requester" LINK "AutoClock"}.

          - Preferences... [RET]
          Brings up the @{"Preferences requester" LINK "Prefs"}.

          - Save Screen...
          Brings up a File Requester to allow you to save the current
          screen display as an IFF file.  This can be loaded into any
          program  that  accepts  an  IFF  picture  in  "ILBM" format
          (eg: Deluxe Paint).

          - Quit           [Q]
          Allows you to quit the program.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "FindMenu" "FIND MENU"
@TOC "MainScr"

          FIND MENU.

          - Mercury        [F1]
          - Venus          [F2]
          - Mars           [F3]
          - Jupiter        [F4]
          - Saturn         [F5]
          - Uranus         [F6]
          - Neptune        [F7]
          - Pluto          [F8]
          - Sun            [F9]
          - Moon           [F10]
          - Earth                              (@{"Orbit Mode" LINK "OrbitMode"} only).
          Causes the observer to look towards the desired object.

          - New Moon
          Finds  the  nearest  occurance  of New Moon within about 2 weeks
          either side of the current calendar setting.

          - Full Moon
          Finds  the  nearest  occurance of Full Moon within about 2 weeks
          either side of the current calendar setting.

          - Object...      [?]                 (@{"Sky Mode" LINK "SkyMode"} only).
          Enables  you  to  ask  the  program  to  find  a star, planet or
          constellation by giving it's name.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "AnimMenu" "ANIM MENU"
@TOC "MainScr"

          ANIM MENU

          See the @{"Animation System" LINK "Anim"} for full details of how animations work.

          - Load...
          Allows you to load a previously saved animation sequence.

          - Save...
          Allows you to save the currently stored animation sequence.

          - Record         [r]
          Starts continuous recording of animation frames.

          - Record Once    [o]
          Records the current @{"Main Screen" LINK "MainScr"} as a single animation frame.

          - Play           [p]
          Starts replaying the currently stored animation sequence.

          - Reverse Play   [v]
          Starts replaying  the  currently  stored  animation  sequence in
          reverse order.

          - Frame Advance  [>]
          Advances to the next animation frame and displays it.

          - Frame Back     [<]
          Goes back to the previous animation frame and displays it.

          - Stop           [SPACE]
          Stops the current animation recording or playback operation.

          - Delete Current [X]
          Deletes the current animation frame.

          - Delete All
          Deletes all stored animation frames.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "ViewMenu" "VIEW MENU"
@TOC "MainScr"

          VIEW MENU

          - Refresh        [HELP]
          Redraws  the  current @{"Main Screen" LINK "MainScr"}.  This is useful after playing
          an animation sequence, or when using the "Trail" option.

          - Look Up        [UP ARROW]                   (@{"Sky Mode" LINK "SkyMode"} only).
          Causes the observer to look higher in the sky,
          ie: increases the observer's viewing altitude.

          - Look Down      [DOWN ARROW]                 (Sky Mode only).
          Causes the observer to look lower in the sky,
          ie: Decreases the observer's viewing altitude.

          - Turn Left      [LEFT ARROW]                 (Sky Mode only).
          Causes the observer to rotate left,
          ie: Reduces the observer's viewing azimuth.

          - Turn Right     [RIGHT ARROW]                (Sky Mode only).
          Causes the observer to rotate right,
          ie: Increases the observer's viewing azimuth.

          - Zoom In        [+]
          Increases the magnification of the observer's view.
          Effectively  behaves as if  you are looking  through a  more and
          more powerful telephoto lens.

          - Zoom Out       [-]
          Decreases the magnification of the observer's view.
          Effectively  behaves as if  you are looking  through a  more and
          more wide angle lens.

          - Face North     [n]                        (Sky Mode only).
          Causes the observer to face directly North.

          - Face South     [s]                        (Sky Mode only).
          Causes the observer to face directly South.

          - Face East      [e]                        (Sky Mode only).
          Causes the observer to face directly East.

          - Face West      [w]                        (Sky Mode only).
          Causes the observer to face directly West.

          - Face Zenith    [z]                        (Sky Mode only).
          Causes the observer to look directly overhead.

          - Face Horizon   [h]                        (Sky Mode only).
          Causes the observer to look towards the horizon.

          - No Tracking    [ESC]
          If any object is being "Tracked" then this effect is cancelled.

          - Rotate Up      [UP ARROW]                 (@{"Orbit Mode" LINK "OrbitMode"} only).
          Increases the observer's view angle.

          - Rotate Down    [DOWN ARROW]               (Orbit Mode only).
          Decreases the observer's view angle.

          - Face On        [f]                        (Orbit Mode only).
          Causes the observer to view the Solar System from above
          ie: Sets the Observer's view angle to 0 degrees.

          - Edge On        [e]                        (Orbit Mode only).
          Causes the observer to view the Solar System from the side
          ie: Sets the Observer's view angle to 90 degrees.

          The  effect of Look/Rotate Up/Down, Turn Left/Right, Zoom In/Out
          can  be  doubled  by  holding  down  [SHIFT],  and quadrupled by
          holding down [ALT].

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Limit" "Limitations"
@TOC "MAIN"

          Limitations.

          This  is  only version 1 of a rather complex program, and it has
          several   limitations  which  are  listed  under  the  following
          headings:

          @{"OS2.0+" LINK "OS20"}
          @{"Screen" LINK "Screen"}
          @{"Speed" LINK "Speed"}
          @{"Memory" LINK "Memory"}
          @{"Database" LINK "DBase"}
          @{"Planets" LINK "Planets"}
          @{"Moon" LINK "MoonDisp"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "OS20" "OS2.0+ Limitations"
@TOC "Limit"

          OS2.0+

          The  program  was written and tested on an Amiga 500 with OS1.3.
          It  was  found to not work properly on the very newest OS2.0 and
          was  shelved.   Recently,  it  was  found to work on OS3.1 and I
          suspect  that  the  particular  2.0  machine  I tested it on was
          faulty.  Since it works on my A1200 (OS3.1) I decided to release
          it  and  hope  it works on all Amigas.  I would be interested to
          hear from anyone who has problems in this area.  Also, since the
          old Amigas didn't have Locales, this program does not know about
          any  of  that  and uses it's own world map.  This also means the
          time zones are not very accurate.  If I ever write version 2, it
          will support the new features of the OS.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Screen" "Screen Dimensions"
@TOC "Limit"

          Screen Dimensions

          The  program was written before I discovered overscan, so it has
          a  fixed  screen width  of  320 and a height of 256 (PAL) or 200
          (NTSC).   If  I  write version 2, it will have more control over
          screen dimensions :)

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Speed" "Speed"
@TOC "Limit"
 
          Speed.

          Much  effort was put into making the program as fast and easy to
          use as possible.  It is written entirely in 68000 assembler, and
          uses  double precision floating point maths, with look-up tables
          for  Sine,  Cosine  etc.   When all options are switched on (ie:
          all  objects,  and  very dim stars), it can take many seconds to
          calculate  a  new  display.  When  the "@{"More Precise" LINK "Prefs"}"  option is
          enabled, this time delay is increased manyfold.  If I ever write
          version  2, I shall look into more efficient algorithms for only
          computing objects that are going to appear on the screen.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Memory" "Memory"
@TOC "Limit"

          Memory.

          The  program  works  best  on a machine with a memory expansion.
          The  more  memory  you  have, the more animations frames you can
          store.   You  can use the program on a 512k machine, but it will
          probably  not  be  possible  to  load  the  star  database  (See
          Configuration Screen) without having memory problems later on.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "DBase" "Database"
@TOC "Limit"

          Database.

          The   program  contains  a  database  of  about  1500  stars  of
          magnitudes  down  to 5.5 There are no galaxies or nebulas in the
          database.  If I ever get time to write version 2, I will attempt
          to incorporate a much larger database.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Planets" "Planet Positions"
@TOC "Limit"

          Planet Positions.

          This  version of the program does not calculate the positions of
          the outer planets to as much accuracy as I would have liked.  In
          addition,  the position of Pluto is only approximate.  According
          to  my  books, there is no known formula for calculating Pluto's
          position  for  ANY  time.  But it can be done for a certain time
          with an increasing error as you move into the past or future.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "MoonDisp" "Moon Display"
@TOC "Limit"

          Moon Display.

          The  display  of  the  Moon does not show the orientation of the
          craters  very  accurately.  It also does not allow for Libration
          (wobbling motions).

@ENDNODE

