@NODE "Notes" "Author's Personal Notes"
@TOC "MAIN"

          Author's Personal Notes.

          I  have  been interested in astronomy since I was a small child,
          when  I was given a book entitled "Wonders of Space".  I read it
          every  night for years.  When I grew up and had to face the real
          world,  I  lost  touch  with  my  love  of the stars.  Living in
          Croydon  didn't help.  Over the last 20 years or so, the problem
          of  light pollution has grown so much that there is now no point
          in me ever looking North.  All I can see is the orange glow from
          London.  I'm sure I could read by it sometimes!

          It  was  in  November  1989  that  I  came into possession of an
          excellent  PD  planetarium  program by Deltron for the Atari ST.
          This  program  rekindled  my  interest  in  astronomy like never
          before.

          Pink  Mouse's Planetarium was born out of a dream I had in which
          I  had  a  kind  of  video control of the sky.  I could run time
          backwards  and  forwards, and watch the heavens unfold before my
          eyes.   After  that dream, I wanted to build my own planetarium,
          but  being  a  man  of  little  knowledge  of building, and more
          important, of insufficient funds, I decided that the only course
          of  action  was to do it the only way I knew how.  So, under the
          expert  supervision  of  my  friend Pink Mouse, I set to work in
          early May 1991.

          The  program  was  almost finished by October, but due to severe
          personal problems, I was unable to continue it.  Very little was
          done during the remainder of 1991 and much of 1992.

          I  finally  completed  it  in  January 1993, but found two major
          problems:

          1) It did not fit on a single floppy disk.
          2) It did not work properly when I tried it on a new @{"V2.0" LINK "OS20"} Amiga.

          The first problem limits the program to users with large storage
          devices  (eg:   Hard  Disk),  but since I'm releasing it through
          Internet now, that is not really a problem anymore.

          The  second  problem  was  the  most  annoying since I had taken
          special  care  to  make  sure  I  followed  all  the programming
          precautions in the Amiga manuals.  I couldn't find any "fiddles"
          or "hacks" that would go against the programming rules laid down
          in  the  manuals.   I  was  so fed up about this at first that I
          couldn't  be  bothered to release the program.  I've since found
          that  it  DOES  work  on  the  new  machines,  so I have renewed
          interest in releasing it, nearly two years after finishing it :)

          I  hope  this  program  gives you a lot of pleasure.  Perhaps it
          will  rekindle an interest in astromomy that you thought you had
          lost.   I  hope  it  will be put to good use in educating people
          about  the  beauty  of  the  Universe  we  live in.  If you have
          children, nieces or nephews, please show it to them.  Teach them
          to  look  up  at  the  sky and see it in a new and exciting way.
          Show them events that happened before they were born, and events
          that  will  happen  long after they are gone from this world.  I
          live  in the hope that one day we will stop wasting time blowing
          each  other  up, and instead start working together to find ways
          to get out there and start exploring strange new worlds.

                            John Croudy

                            Croydon, England, October 1995


          "Life  can  only  be  understood backwards, but it must be lived
           forwards"
                             Kierkegaard

@ENDNODE

